<td bgcolor=ffffff>
<a href="search.php?query=&topic=34&author="><img src=images/topics/optimus.jpg border=0 Alt="Optimus" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10></a>
If you ever, ever, ever get an unsolicited email with a disclaimer at the bottom with some horseshit that says:
<br><br>
"Note: We respect your on line privacy.This is not an unsolicited mail. Under Bill s.1618 Title III passed by the 105th US Congress this mail cannot be considered Spam as long as we include contact information and a method to be removed from our mailing list. If you are not interested in receiving our e-mails then please reply with a "Remove" in the subject line. I am sorry for the inconvenience caused to you."
<br><br>
Please point them to:<br><br>

<a href="http://www.cauce.org/legislation/s1618_hr3888.shtml" target=_blank>Information about S. 1618 / H.R. 3888 (original draft)
Title III - Spamming Legislation</a><br>Which essentially states:<br> <b>The legislation for S. 1618 / H.R. 3888 died at the end of the 105th Congress in 1998. In other words, it's not law, never was law, and never will be law.</b><br><br>
Then of course feel free to RBL them or whatever the hell. And fyi, as quoted from <a href="http://www.suespammers.org" target=_blank>SueSpammers.org</a>, "There are currently no U.S. Federal laws specifically regarding spam. However, spammers have lost in Federal cases that cited other laws, such as those for trespass and forgery..."
<p>
Please also check out <a href="http://www.cauce.org" target=_blank>Cauce.org</a> for more information about spam. And while there is no federal legislation passed into law yet, there have been several state laws passed regarding unsolicited email.<p>
The fuckers.<br><br>
-Optimus<br>
Who clearly has been dealing with a spamming issue from some asshole for way too long now.<br><br>
